It reviews existing findings and presents new analyses of data from the British Household Panel Survey. The same 10,000 adults (in 5,000 households) have been interviewed every year between 1991 and 1997. Seven years in the lives of British families is a collaboration between members of the University of Essex's Institute for Social and Economic Research. Each of the authors is an expert in the field, but the work has been presented in an easy-to-read style to make these important research findings widely accessible. The book will be read by policy makers and all with an interest in the dynamics of modern society, as well as by academic sociologists, economists and demographers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Marriage & Family.2bisacsh1 aBerthoud, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerthoud, Richard, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBrynin, Malcolm, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuck, Nick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErmisch, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrancesconi, Marco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGershuny, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGershuny, Jonathan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJenkins, Stephen P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaurie, Heather, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTaylor, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-1995z978311119621340uhttps://www.degruy